e move is to re-confirm Nomonde still owns procurement tech selection or identify her successor."}, "competition": {"status": "partial", "sources": ["Avoma call 2 Apr 2025 (Denver Archary, Jochen Werner)", "Avoma call 28 Mar 2025 (Nomonde Thabethe)", "Prior canonical record (incumbent carried forward)"], "narrative": "This is a replacement deal, not an active bake-off: the buyer is displacing an unnamed incumbent procurement provider they have used 'for many years' and is running a parallel group finance/ERP transformation (Microsoft Dynamics is going end-of-life around 2027-2028). No competitor is currently preferred over Zycus. Coupa surfaced only as background (Zycus's own VP previously worked there, and Zycus disparaged it post-Thoma-Bravo acquisition); the buyer noted Coupa's Gartner standing neutrally but showed no lean. Denver did note 'there are other solutions we are within budget on the costing' (2 Apr 2025), so price-competitive alternatives exist even if unnamed. The competitive risk is displacement-by-ERP (if the new finance platform bundles procurement) plus the budget gap, not a named rival winning."}, "identify_pain": {"status": "confirmed", "sources": ["Avoma call 28 Mar 2025 (Nomonde Thabethe)", "Avoma call 2 Apr 2025 (Denver Archary)"], "narrative": "Confirmed operational pain: fully manual, spreadsheet-driven contract management and inefficient sourcing across a fragmented insurance group. Nomonde Thabethe stated 'we do contracts manually... it's very painful and we need to automate in order for us to be able to create efficiencies and deliver on time' (28 Mar 2025) and described audit exposure and high contract volumes (2,000-3,000 group contracts, 500+ claims panel contracts). The pain owner is group procurement (Nomonde and Denver), with claims, life and broker teams as downstream stakeholders. The pain is real but deprioritised beneath the group finance/ERP transformation, which is why procurement chose to move first on sourcing only."}, "paper_process": {"status": "partial", "sources": ["Avoma call 2 Apr 2025 (Denver Archary)"], "narrative": "Contracting mechanics were discussed at a high level: a five-year SaaS agreement, monthly-in-advance SaaS billing and milestone-based implementation payments, a scoping workshop on signature, and an IT governance path (Arc Forum, cloud assessment, InfoSec) that the buyer expected to be lengthy. Denver referenced an internal IT contact ('Bill Cobb... he was quite impressed... but he'd have to apply the full IT governance process', 2 Apr 2025). No MSA/SOW, legal review or procurement channel was ever formalised because the deal never cleared budget approval. Current-contract expiry on the incumbent was cited as roughly 2026, which could become a forcing function if the deal reactivates."}, "economic_buyer": {"status": "gap", "sources": ["Avoma call 2 Apr 2025 (Denver Archary)", "Avoma call 28 Mar 2025 (Nomonde Thabethe)", "OpportunityContactRole (no EB role recorded)"], "narrative": "No economic buyer is named in Salesforce contact roles or confirmed on any call. Denver Archary (Procurement Manager) repeatedly deferred final approval to his leadership ('I need to then do a business case and motivation and then speak to my management team to see what the appetite is', 2 Apr 2025), and Nomonde noted procurement is structurally last in line for funding ('procurement when it comes to funding of technology we always the last people to be considered', 28 Mar 2025). Budget authority sits with the finance-transformation / group leadership tied to the broader ERP replacement of Microsoft Dynamics, but that person has never been engaged, named, or put on a call. The move is to have Denver or Nomonde name and introduce the budget owner before any re-quote."}, "decision_process": {"status": "partial", "sources": ["Avoma call 2 Apr 2025 (Nomonde Thabethe)", "Avoma call 28 Mar 2025 (Nomonde Thabethe, Denver Archary)"], "narrative": "The buyer described a multi-gate process: secur